---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import AdUnit from '../../components/AdUnit.astro';

const faq = [
  { question: "What is tig?", answer: "tig is a text-mode interface for Git, written in C by Jonas Fonseca. It provides a terminal-based viewer for Git history, branches, blame, diffs, staging, and the reflog. tig is primarily a read-heavy tool — excellent for browsing and exploring Git history — though it also supports some write operations like staging/unstaging and stash management. It runs in any terminal and works over SSH." },
  { question: "How does tig compare to lazygit?", answer: "tig is best described as a powerful Git viewer — it excels at browsing history, blame, and diffs in a clean TUI. lazygit is an action-first Git client designed for the full workflow: staging hunks, committing, branching, rebasing, pushing. tig has better history browsing and blame views; lazygit has better interactive operations. Many developers use both: tig for reading history and blame, lazygit for active Git work." },
  { question: "What are the main tig views?", answer: "tig has six main views: Main view (git log graph), Diff view (the diff for the selected commit), Log view (git log output), Tree view (file tree for any commit), Blob view (file contents at any commit), and Blame view (git blame). Press 't' to open the tree, 'b' for blame, 'd' for diff, 'l' for log, 'r' for refs/branches. Press 'h' inside tig to see all key bindings." },
  { question: "What are the most useful tig keybindings?", answer: "Essential tig keys: 'j/k' or arrow keys to navigate, 'Enter' to open the diff for a commit, 'Tab' to switch between the main view and diff pane, 'q' to quit the current view (or tig entirely), '/' to search, 'n' for next match, 'p' for previous match. In the main view: 'm' opens the main view, 't' opens the tree, 'b' opens blame, 'r' opens the refs view for branches and tags. 'h' or 'F1' shows the full keybinding reference." },
  { question: "Can I use tig for staging and committing?", answer: "Yes, but it is not tig's strength. Run 'tig status' (or press 'S' from within tig) to open the status view. In the status view, press 'u' to stage/unstage a file, 'C' to commit. tig does not support hunk-level staging (you can't stage individual diff hunks inside tig). For hunk staging, use 'git add -p' or switch to lazygit." },
  { question: "How do I customize tig?", answer: "tig reads configuration from ~/.tigrc (or $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/tig/config). You can set key bindings, colors, column formats, and view options. Example: 'set show-notes = yes' to show git notes, 'set tab-size = 4' to set tab width, 'bind generic <C-r> !git rebase -i %(commit)' to add a custom keybinding that triggers git rebase. Run 'tig --help' or see the tig manual page for all options." },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="tig — Text-Mode Interface for Git"
  description="tig is a terminal UI for browsing Git history, blame, diffs, and branches. Keyboard-driven TUI with log, diff, tree, and blame views. Install via brew or apt. Free and open source."
  tool="tig git, tig terminal UI, git TUI browser, git log TUI, git blame terminal, tig vs lazygit"
  faq={faq}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebPage",
    "name": "tig — Text-Mode Interface for Git",
    "url": "https://devplaybook.cc/tools/tig",
    "description": "tig is a terminal UI for browsing Git history, blame, diffs, and branches. Keyboard-driven TUI with log, diff, tree, and blame views.",
  })} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">tig</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">
    A <strong>text-mode interface for Git</strong> written in C. tig provides a keyboard-driven terminal UI
    for browsing Git history, blame, diffs, branches, and file trees — fast and works anywhere you have
    a terminal, including over SSH.
  </p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Terminal-native (no GUI needed)</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> History / blame / diff views</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Works over SSH</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Open source (GPL-2.0)</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">What is tig?</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4 leading-relaxed">
    tig (by Jonas Fonseca) is a curses-based text UI for Git, primarily designed for reading and exploring repositories. It wraps common Git commands — git log, git show, git blame, git diff — in a navigable split-pane interface. You can browse commit history, inspect diffs, view file trees at any commit, read blame annotations, and search through log output, all without leaving your terminal.
  </p>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4 leading-relaxed">
    tig is a popular complement to command-line workflows and terminal-centric editors. It is especially valuable on remote servers where GUI tools are unavailable. While lazygit focuses on Git operations, tig focuses on Git exploration — making it the go-to tool for understanding a repository's history.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Key Features</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-muted space-y-1 mb-4 ml-2">
    <li><strong>Log / Main view</strong> — git log with graph lines, author, date, and subject in a scrollable list</li>
    <li><strong>Diff view</strong> — split-pane diff for any selected commit, syntax-colored</li>
    <li><strong>Branch / Refs view</strong> — list all local and remote branches, tags, and stashes</li>
    <li><strong>Blame view</strong> — git blame with commit info and navigation to the blamed commit's diff</li>
    <li><strong>Tree view</strong> — browse the file tree as it existed at any commit</li>
    <li><strong>Status view</strong> — basic staging and unstaging (whole files, not hunks)</li>
    <li><strong>Search</strong> — '/' to search within any view, 'n'/'N' to navigate matches</li>
    <li><strong>Custom key bindings</strong> — bind any shell command or git operation to a key in ~/.tigrc</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Installation</h2>
  <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-xs font-mono overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre text-text mb-2"># macOS (Homebrew)
brew install tig

# Ubuntu / Debian
apt install tig

# Fedora / RHEL
dnf install tig

# Arch Linux
pacman -S tig

# Windows (Scoop)
scoop install tig

# Build from source
git clone https://github.com/jonas/tig
cd tig &amp;&amp; make &amp;&amp; sudo make install</pre>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Essential Keybindings</h2>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-bg-card">
          <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left">Key</th>
          <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left">Action</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono">j / k</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Navigate up / down</td></tr>
        <tr class="bg-bg-card/30"><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono">Enter</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Open diff for selected commit</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono">Tab</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Toggle between log and diff panes</td></tr>
        <tr class="bg-bg-card/30"><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono">q</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Close current view (Q to quit tig)</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono">t</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Open tree view (file browser)</td></tr>
        <tr class="bg-bg-card/30"><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono">b</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Open blame view</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono">r</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Open refs view (branches/tags)</td></tr>
        <tr class="bg-bg-card/30"><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono">S</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Open status view (staging)</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono">/</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Search in current view</td></tr>
        <tr class="bg-bg-card/30"><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono">n / N</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Next / previous search match</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono">g</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Jump to first line</td></tr>
        <tr class="bg-bg-card/30"><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono">G</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Jump to last line</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono">h / F1</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Show help and full key reference</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Common tig Commands</h2>
  <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-xs font-mono overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre text-text mb-4"># Open tig in the current repo (main log view)
tig

# Browse a specific branch
tig main

# Browse commits affecting a specific file
tig -- src/auth.ts

# Open blame view for a file directly
tig blame src/auth.ts

# Open status view for staging
tig status

# Browse the reflog
tig reflog

# Filter log by author
tig --author="Alice"</pre>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Use Cases</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-muted space-y-1 mb-4 ml-2">
    <li>Exploring a new repository's history to understand its development timeline</li>
    <li>Investigating when and where a bug was introduced using the blame view</li>
    <li>Browsing file contents at any historical commit via the tree view</li>
    <li>Reviewing commit diffs on a remote server without a GUI</li>
    <li>Finding a specific change by searching the commit log</li>
    <li>Getting a quick visual overview of branch state in the refs view</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Pros and Cons</h2>
  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-6">
    <div class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-green-400 mb-2">Pros</h3>
      <ul class="text-text-muted text-sm space-y-1">
        <li>✓ Excellent history browsing and blame navigation</li>
        <li>✓ Very lightweight C binary — available on almost any Linux system</li>
        <li>✓ Works over SSH without any setup on the remote</li>
        <li>✓ Fast even on large repositories</li>
        <li>✓ Highly customizable via ~/.tigrc</li>
        <li>✓ Stable and battle-tested (10+ years old)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-red-400 mb-2">Cons</h3>
      <ul class="text-text-muted text-sm space-y-1">
        <li>✗ No hunk-level staging (use git add -p or lazygit instead)</li>
        <li>✗ Limited write/action support compared to lazygit</li>
        <li>✗ Older curses UI — less polished than newer TUI tools</li>
        <li>✗ No built-in GitHub / GitLab integration</li>
        <li>✗ Keybindings take time to learn and remember</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <AdUnit slot="auto" format="auto" label="Advertisement" />
  <FaqSection faq={faq} />
  <ToolPageCta currentTool="tig" relatedTags={['git', 'cli', 'terminal', 'devops', 'version-control']} />
</BaseLayout>
